If you’d like to test a few sections together, you can start with a minimal HTML skeleton and a bit of CSS that realises the “slow page” idea from your notes.  
Here’s a static‑scroll version; you can place your existing text in each section:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>After Quiet</title>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Gentium+Book+Basic&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
body {
  font-family: 'Gentium Book Basic', serif;
  font-size: 1rem;
  line-height: 1.6;
  color: #222;
  background: #fafafa;
  margin: 0;
}
section {
  min-height: 100vh;             /* one screen per section */
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  justify-content: center;
  padding: 0 8vw;
}
h2 { opacity: 0; animation: fadeIn 2s ease forwards; }
@keyframes fadeIn { from {opacity:0;} to {opacity:1;} }
blockquote.epigraph {
  font-style: italic;
  font-size: 0.9em;
  text-align: center;
  color: #555;
  margin: 60vh 0;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<blockquote class="epigraph">Every silence teaches the shape of hearing.</blockquote>

<section id="one">
  <h2>I. Stillness</h2>
  <p>Before the light, the room is a shape without edges…</p>
</section>

<section id="two">
  <h2>II. First Notice</h2>
  <p>The click becomes a whisper of steam…</p>
</section>

<section id="three">
  <h2>III. Return</h2>
  <p>Steam edges from the kettle, rising in thin spirals…</p>
</section>

</body>
</html>
```

Opening this file in any browser will give you a clean, scroll‑based presentation with one section per screen and a slow fade‑in on each heading.  
You can adjust margins or line height, or add your other sections easily.

Would you like a version that also includes faint “next / previous” links fixed at the edges for non‑scroll navigation?

